    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <!-- Show det(aM) = a det(A), det(AB) = det(A) det(B)-->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p> If <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 5 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>, compute the determinant of <m>A</m>, written <m>\det{A}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We can compute the determinant of a 2 by 2 matrix using the formula <m>\det{\begin{bmatrix} a &amp; b \\ c &amp; d \end{bmatrix}} = ad - bc</m>. In this case, we have <m>a = 5</m>, <m>b = 3</m>, <m>c = 1</m>, and <m>d = 4</m>. Substituting these values into the formula gives us:

                <md>
                    <mrow> \det{A} \amp = (5)(4) - (3)(1) </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp = 20 - 3 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 17 </mrow>
                </md>

                Therefore, the determinant of matrix <m>A</m> is <m>17</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>M = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ 4 &amp; -2 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compute <m>\det{M}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What does the value of the determinant tell us about the inverse of <m>M</m>?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Using the formula for the determinant of a 2 by 2 matrix, we have:

                        <md>
                            <mrow> \det{M} \amp = ad - bc </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = (2)(-2) - (-1)(4) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = -4 + 4 </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = 0 </mrow>
                        </md>

                        Therefore, the determinant of matrix <m>M</m> is <m>0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Since <m>\det{M} = 0</m>, the matrix <m>M</m> does not have an inverse. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This is because any system of equations <m>M\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m> would have either no solutions or infinitely many solutions, depending on the value of <m>\mathbf{b}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        For example, if <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, then we get the system of equations:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> 2x - y \amp = 0 </mrow>
                            <mrow> 4x - 2y \amp = 0 </mrow>
                        </md>
                        These are two parallel lines that coincide, meaning there are infinitely many solutions to this system of equations.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In either case, we cannot find a unique solution for <m>\mathbf{x}</m>, which is why the matrix <m>M</m> does not have an inverse.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}-4 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m> B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compute <m>\det{A}</m> and <m>\det{B}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the product <m>AB</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compute <m>\det{AB}</m> and verify that it is equal to <m>\det{A} \cdot \det{B}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>   
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Finding <m>\det{A}</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \det{A} \amp = ad - bc </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = (-4)(3) - (0)(0) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = -12 </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Finding <m>\det{B}</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \det{B} \amp = ad - bc </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = (1)(2) - (2)(3) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = 2 - 6 </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = -4 </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To find the product <m>AB</m>, we perform matrix multiplication:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> AB \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -4 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} (-4)(1) + (0)(3) \amp (-4)(2) + (0)(2) \\ (0)(1) + (3)(3) \amp (0)(2) + (3)(2) \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -4 \amp -8 \\ 9 \amp 6 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Finding <m>\det{AB}</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \det{AB} \amp = ad - bc </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = (-4)(6) - (-8)(9) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = -24 + 72 </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = 48 </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Now we verify that <m>\det{AB} = \det{A} \cdot \det{B}</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \det{A} \cdot \det{B} \amp = (-12)(-4) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = 48 </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \det{AB} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In fact, the property <m>\det{AB} = \det{A} \cdot \det{B}</m> holds for all matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> (as long as <m>AB</m> is defined).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

